Part 2 of Build A Simple File Explorer in Rust

6 steps

Let's continue building the libfile-explorer crate. In this tutorial, you will write improved code that includes the basic functionalities mentioned from the software architecture documentation. You will continue to write documentation in parts of the code and also add more information to the ARCHITECTURE.md file.

Additionally, you will write unit tests that verifies the intended behaviour of the basic functionalities such as creating a file, deleting a directory and moving files or directories.

For technical help on the StackUp platform & tutorial-related questions, join our Discord, to ask your question.

Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Required to have finished Tutorial 1 of this Learn module.
  • Recommended to have finished Rust Basics.
  • A working Rust installation. For instructions, head to https://rustup.rs/ and follow the platform-specific instructions.
  • Recommended to know Git and GitHub. For a tutorial, head to Version Control Basics with Git and GitHub. Git must be installed and configured before doing this tutorial.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Learn the thought-process of developing from initial idea to actual code.
  • Write basic functionalities of the library.
  • Write tests to match behaviour and function.

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: Initial refactor

    Before starting, ensure that you have finished Tutorial 1 as required. This project will not be possible if you haven't prepared your development environment.

    Let's continue. Remember that the project's root directory is called simple-file-explorer and the library crate's root directory is called libfile-explorer within the simple-file-explorer directory.

    Head to the library crate's root directory. Run the following command.

    cargo add libroast

    This will add libroast, a Rust crate that contains special utilities for archiving files. You will only use the copy_dir_all function from its utils module.

    Head to the src directory. Open and edit the file fs_wrappers.rs. Replace all contents of fs_wrappers.rs with the following code below.

    use std::fs;
use std::io;
use std::os::unix::fs::MetadataExt;
use std::path::Path;
use std::path::PathBuf;
use std::time::SystemTime;

use libroast::utils::copy_dir_all;

/// A representation of what a filesystem has. For now, we have two kinds, it is either
/// a `Directory` or a `File`.
#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
pub enum FsKind {
    Directory,
    File,
}

/// A representation of a filesystem object. For now, it only contains important metadata.
/// This is an initial implementation and will change as the project progresses.
#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
pub struct FsObject {
    pub kind: FsKind,
    pub date_created: SystemTime,
    pub size: u64,
    pub current_path: PathBuf,
}
    Rust

    This refactor is important. The previous code only lays out the ideas but not a working implementation. The FsObject struct now has replaced the type of date_created field with the type SystemTime. This is important because you can access methods from the standard library to properly check dates and time—see documentation for SystemTime.

    Append the following code below to your fs_wrappers.rs.

    /// Initial implementation of the `FsObject` methods.
impl FsObject {
    /// Creates a new FsObject from a path that must exist. If `None` was provided, it assumes the
    /// FsObject is at the current working directory.
    pub fn new(path: Option<PathBuf>) -> io::Result<FsObject> {
        let kind: FsKind;
        let size: u64;
        if let Some(p) = path {
            kind = if p.is_dir() {
                FsKind::Directory
            } else if p.is_file() {
                FsKind::File
            } else {
                return Err(io::Error::new(
                    io::ErrorKind::Unsupported,
                    "Filesystem kind is not supported yet",
                ));
            };
            let metadata = p.metadata()?;
            let date_created = metadata.created()?;
            size = metadata.size();
            Ok(FsObject {
                kind,
                date_created,
                size,
                current_path: p,
            })
        } else {
            // Assume that it's the current working directory
            let current_directory = std::env::current_dir()?;
            let metadata = current_directory.metadata()?;
            let date_created = metadata.created()?;
            size = metadata.size();
            Ok(FsObject {
                kind: FsKind::Directory,
                date_created,
                size,
                current_path: current_directory,
            })
        }
    }

    /// This is just a wrapper around `.exists()` method from `std::path::Path`.
    pub fn exists(&self) -> bool {
        self.current_path.exists()
    }

}
    Rust

    Based on the new code implementation for the FsObject, error handling was also introduced. Before, there were only panic!() and unwrap methods. The new code removed them by introducing the enum Result from the std::io module.

    The replacements for panics and unwraps are more readable, especially the introduction of the control-flow syntax i.e. metadata.created()?. It is marked by a question mark symbol. It is important to introduce error handling early as it is easier to reason during initial stages of development of a project.

    There also exists a .exists method that just calls the .exists method from the std::path module.

    Save the file. Run the following commands on your terminal at the root directory of your project—simple-file-explorer.

git commit -m "chore: begin initial code implementation"
git push

  • Step 2: Functions to create a file and a directory

    In this short step, edit the impl FsObject code block from the fs_wrappers.rs file. Add the following methods to impl FsObject.

        /// This function creates a new file and a new `FsObject`. It's a wrapper from filesystem operations for creating files and directories from the `std::fs` module.
    pub fn create_file(target_path: &Path, _overwrite: bool) -> io::Result<Self> {
        // TODO: add feature to overwrite
        match fs::File::create_new(target_path) {
            Ok(result) => {
                let metadata = result.metadata()?;
                let fs_object = FsObject {
                    kind: FsKind::File,
                    size: metadata.size(),
                    date_created: metadata.created()?,
                    current_path: target_path.to_path_buf(),
                };
                Ok(fs_object)
            }
            Err(err) => Err(err),
        }
    }

    /// This function creates a new directory and a new `FsObject`. It's a wrapper from filesystem operations for creating files and directories from the `std::fs` module.
    pub fn create_dir(target_path: &Path) -> io::Result<Self> {
        match fs::create_dir_all(target_path) {
            Ok(_) => {
                let metadata = target_path.metadata()?;
                let fs_object = FsObject {
                    kind: FsKind::Directory,
                    size: metadata.size(),
                    date_created: metadata.created()?,
                    current_path: target_path.to_path_buf(),
                };
                Ok(fs_object)
            }
            Err(err) => Err(err),
        }
    }
    Rust

    These will create a directory or a file and then return an FsObject within a Result enumeration's Ok variant if it succeeds, otherwise, an Err variant.

  • Step 3: Adding the move, copy and delete functions

    Edit the fs_wrappers.rs file. Add the following methods into the impl FsObject block.

    
    pub fn move_to(&mut self, target_path: &Path) -> io::Result<()> {
        match self.kind {
            // WARNING: Destructive operation. On most file explorers, moving a directory is possible if the source directory
            // is empty and the target directory is also empty or does not exist. Our function's behaviour is different since
            // 1. It will delete the target directory first if it exists.
            // 2. Copies the source directory alongside its contents to the target directory.
            // 3. Deletes the source directory after.
            // This behaviour is not ideal but it will do for now.
            FsKind::Directory => {
                // We first delete the target directory, `target_path`, regardless if it is empty or not.
                if target_path.is_dir() && target_path.exists() {
                    fs::remove_dir_all(target_path)?;
                }
                copy_dir_all(&self.current_path, target_path)?;
                fs::remove_dir_all(&self.current_path)?;
                self.current_path = target_path.to_path_buf();
            }
            FsKind::File => {
                // The `fs::rename` function is oddly named but it's actually just renaming the path instead of the filename.
                // WARNING: Destructive operation. This will replace the file at the `target_path` if it exists.
                fs::rename(&self.current_path, target_path)?;
                self.current_path = target_path.to_path_buf();
            }
        }
        Ok(())
    }

    pub fn copy_to(&self, target_path: &Path) -> io::Result<()> {
        match self.kind {
            FsKind::Directory => copy_dir_all(&self.current_path, target_path),
            FsKind::File => match fs::copy(&self.current_path, target_path) {
                // NOTE: We might want to print debug statements in the future.
                Ok(_) => Ok(()),
                Err(err) => Err(err),
            },
        }
    }

    /// This function transfers ownership within the method. Since ownership is transferred,
    /// the value is moved out of scope and never returned.
    pub fn delete(self) -> io::Result<()> {
        if self.current_path.is_file() {
            fs::remove_file(&self.current_path)?;
        } else if self.current_path.is_dir() {
            // NOTE: Should we remove all contents within a directory or remove them
            // only if it's empty?
            fs::remove_dir_all(&self.current_path)?;
        } else {
            return Err(io::Error::new(
                io::ErrorKind::Other,
                "Operation is not supported",
            ));
        };
        Ok(())
    }
    Rust

    As observed, both copy_to and move_to methods are similar. The only difference is that move_to removes the original path. Both also use the copy_dir_all from the libroast crate for copying directories to the target path.

    The delete method takes ownership as compared to the other two methods—see &self vs self. This is intentional to forcibly drop the value as it won't make sense to still have a reference of an FsObject that points to a path that does not exist.

    Although there is a exists method, the exists method serves as a utility to ensure that the path to a file or a directory still exists. This is useful for cases where a user uses two different file explorers and deletes a file or directory in either of them.

    Save the file. Run the following commands at the libfile-explorer directory.

    Adding the test cases

    Append the following functions into the tests module block.

        fn test_moving_a_file() -> io::Result<()> {
        let temporary_dir = tempfile::TempDir::new()?;
        let file_path = temporary_dir.path().join("source.txt");
        let mut source_file = std::fs::File::create(&file_path)?;
        let target_file_path = temporary_dir.path().join("target.txt");
        let mut rng = rand::rng();
        let mut data = [0u8; 32];
        rng.fill_bytes(&mut data);
        source_file.write_all(&mut data)?;

        let mut hash1 = Hasher::default();
        let source_bytes = std::fs::read(&file_path)?;

        let mut fs_object_from_source = FsObject::new(Some(file_path.to_path_buf()))?;
        fs_object_from_source.move_to(&target_file_path)?;

        let mut hash2 = Hasher::default();

        let target_bytes = std::fs::read(&target_file_path)?;

        hash1.update(&source_bytes);
        hash2.update(&target_bytes);

        assert!(hash1.finalize() == hash2.finalize()); // Hashes for both files should be the same.

        // After moving file
        assert!(&fs_object_from_source.exists()); // It should still exist but now on the new path.
        assert!(*fs_object_from_source.current_path != file_path); // Old path vs new path should not be the same.
        assert!(*fs_object_from_source.current_path == target_file_path); // Path should be updated.
        assert!(target_file_path.exists());
        Ok(())
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_moving_a_directory() -> io::Result<()> {
        let temporary_dir = tempfile::TempDir::new()?;
        let directory_path = temporary_dir.path().join("some_directory");
        let source_archive_path = temporary_dir.path().join("source.tar");
        let move_target_path = temporary_dir.path().join("target_directory");
        let target_archive_path = temporary_dir.path().join("target.tar");

        let mut fs_object = FsObject::create_dir(&directory_path)?;

        // Add some random files with random data inside
        for _ in 0..300 {
            let rng = rand::rng();
            let mut data = [0u8; 32];
            let filename: String = rng
                .sample_iter(rand::distr::Alphanumeric)
                .take(8)
                .map(char::from)
                .collect();
            let some_file_path = directory_path.join(&filename);
            let mut file = std::fs::File::create(&some_file_path)?;
            let mut rng = rand::rng();
            rng.fill_bytes(&mut data);
            file.write_all(&mut data)?;
        }

        let first_roast_args = libroast::operations::cli::RoastArgs {
            target: directory_path.to_path_buf(),
            include: None,
            exclude: None,
            additional_paths: None,
            outfile: source_archive_path.to_path_buf(),
            outdir: None,
            preserve_root: false,
            reproducible: true,
            ignore_git: false,
            ignore_hidden: false,
        };
        libroast::operations::roast::roast_opts(&first_roast_args, false)?;

        let mut hash1 = Hasher::default();
        let source_bytes = std::fs::read(&source_archive_path)?;
        hash1.update(&source_bytes);

        fs_object.move_to(&move_target_path)?;
        let second_roast_args = libroast::operations::cli::RoastArgs {
            target: move_target_path.to_path_buf(),
            include: None,
            exclude: None,
            additional_paths: None,
            outfile: target_archive_path.to_path_buf(),
            outdir: None,
            preserve_root: false,
            reproducible: true,
            ignore_git: false,
            ignore_hidden: false,
        };
        libroast::operations::roast::roast_opts(&second_roast_args, false)?;

        let mut hash2 = Hasher::default();
        let target_bytes = std::fs::read(&target_archive_path)?;
        hash2.update(&target_bytes);

        assert!(hash1.finalize() == hash2.finalize()); // Tarballs should be of the same hash
        assert!(fs_object.current_path == move_target_path); // The path should be updated to the new path.
        assert!(move_target_path.exists());

        Ok(())
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_deleting_a_file() -> io::Result<()> {
        let temporary_dir = tempfile::TempDir::new()?;
        let file_path = temporary_dir.path().join("source.txt");
        let mut source_file = std::fs::File::create(&file_path)?;

        // was dropped, the path should not exist anymore.

        Ok(())
    }

    Rust

    Carefully read each code comment. As observed, it's easy to generate hashes between files to compare that both files from the original source and the copy are the same using the blake3 crate's Hasher constructor. But what about directories?

    In the case of directories, the code uses libroast crate's operations module, specifically, the roast_opts function. The roast_opts function generates a tarball from a source—a directory. An archive or tarball is a file that is a packed version of files or directories. This allows comparison between the hashes of the original directory and the copied or moved directory but as files.

    However, generating an archive or tarball is usually nondeterministic—this means a similar input will generate a different output, despite two archives having similar contents—e.g. due to different metadata, arrangements of files—hence, producing a different hash.

    Fortunately, libroast allows deterministic generation of tarballs by just passing "true" to the "reproducible" field from the RoastArgs constructor. This ensures that even with randomized filenames with randomized file contents, two directories are one and the same based on deterministic outputs—filenames are sorted, metadata are the same.

    💡 Reproducibility is a topic that might need to be discussed in the future but it is out of scope of this Learn module.

  • Step 4: Adding utility methods

    In this step, let's add two more utility functions—listing files and directories. This is also a required functionality. You will write two variants: one for listing all paths, and the second for listing generated FsObject per path.

    Edit the fs_wrappers.rs file. Append the following code just outside of impl FsObject.

    /// This function will list directories and files at the top-level of the target path `p`.
pub fn list(p: &Path) -> io::Result<Vec<PathBuf>> {
    if p.is_file() {
        // If the path is a file, only list the file.
        Ok(vec![p.to_path_buf()])
    } else if p.is_dir() {
        let read_dir = p.read_dir()?;
        let result: Vec<PathBuf> = read_dir
            .into_iter()
            .flatten()
            .map(|dir_entry| dir_entry.path())
            .filter(|dir| dir.exists())
            .collect();
        return Ok(result);
    } else {
        return Err(io::Error::new(
            io::ErrorKind::Other,
            "Cannot list specified path!",
        ));
    }
}

/// This function will list directories and files but in a more detailed form.
pub fn list_with_details(p: &Path) -> io::Result<Vec<FsObject>> {
    let list: Vec<PathBuf> = super::fs_wrappers::list(p)?;
    Ok(list
        .iter()
        .flat_map(|path| FsObject::new(Some(path.to_path_buf())))
        .collect())
}
    Rust

    Just within the impl FsObject, add the following methods that are just wrappers of the previous code you appended.

        /// This is a wrapper around the `super::fs_wrappers::list` function.
    pub fn list(&self) -> io::Result<Vec<PathBuf>> {
        super::fs_wrappers::list(&self.current_path)
    }

    /// This is a wrapper around the `super::fs_wrappers::list_with_details` function.
    pub fn list_with_details(&self) -> io::Result<Vec<FsObject>> {
        super::fs_wrappers::list_with_details(&self.current_path)
    }
    Rust

## Library

The library provides functions that extends or integrates the `fs` and `path` modules from the Rust
standard library, `std`. The library can be split into the following modules.

- `fs_wrappers` contains file operations that extend the functionality of the `fs` module.
- `json_api` contains the JSON API logic that accepts input and performs filesystem operations based on the input received.
- `prelude` contains most commonly exported functions. This is optional and possibly be removed if there is no benefit at all if including this.

### `fs_wrappers`

The `fs_wrappers` module contains functions that wraps around mainly from the `std::path` and the `std::fs` modules from the standard library. It's primarily focused on basic functionalities:

- showing file and directory information,
- listing files and directories at a specified path i.e. based from an `FsObject`.
- file explorer operations:
  - creating a file or directory
  - deleting a file or directory
  - moving a file or directory
  - copying a file or directory
